with sound fiscal policy; and
WHEREAS, providing recurring compensation increases for teachers and support
staff requires a stable, predictable, and permanent source of revenue; and
WHEREAS, Constitutional Amendment 2, was submitted to voters on the March 29,
2025, statewide election, as part of a broader revision of Article VII of the Constitution of
Louisiana, proposed, among other things, to redirect certain education trust funds and utilize
resulting retirement system savings to support permanent pay increases of $2,000 for
teachers and $1,000 for support staff, but was rejected by the voters; and
WHEREAS, Constitutional Amendment 3, submitted to voters at the May 16, 2026,
statewide election, proposed a substantially similar approach to fund permanent pay
increases of $2,250 for teachers and $1,125 for support staff using redirected trust funds and
retirement system savings, and was likewise rejected by the voters for a second time; and
WHEREAS, the recent failure of Constitutional Amendment 3, when considered
together with the Revenue Estimating Conference's downward revision of the official state
revenue forecast by over $100 million, has left unresolved the replacement of temporary
stipends with permanent pay increases for teachers and has heightened uncertainty for
employees and school systems preparing salary schedules and budgets for the 2026-2027
school year; and
WHEREAS, these circumstances underscore the need for a funding structure for
teacher and support staff compensation that is not dependent on temporary mechanisms,
redirection of existing funds, or one-time solutions, but instead is grounded in a stable,
transparent, and sustainable framework within the state's core education funding system; and
WHEREAS, such uncertainty complicates local school system budgeting,
undermines workforce stability, and impairs the ability of school systems to recruit and
retain qualified teachers and support staff, particularly in advance of the 2026-2027 school
year; and
WHEREAS, the Minimum Foundation Program (MFP) is established in Article VIII,
Section 13(B) of the Constitution of Louisiana and serves as the framework through which
the state determines the cost of a minimum foundation program of education and equitably
allocates funding to parish and city school systems; and
