WHEREAS, resolving the challenge of providing permanent, predictable
compensation for teachers and support staff requires a comprehensive evaluation of the MFP
and the state's primary constitutional mechanism for funding public education; and
WHEREAS, the MFP formula has retained its core architecture since 1992, when a
major revision shifted the state from an expenditure-driven model to a student-driven
formula intended to promote equity in the distribution of educational resources; and
WHEREAS, since that time, the MFP has evolved from two principal components
of state and local contributions with student-based weights into a four-level structure
incorporating additional policy choices, legacy allocations, and adjustments layered over
decades; and
WHEREAS, while these additions have addressed specific needs over time, their
cumulative effect has resulted in a formula that reflects incremental policymaking rather
than a comprehensive, modern design aligned with current fiscal realities and workforce
priorities; and
WHEREAS, MFP Level 1 determines the minimum cost of education based on the
educational needs of each student, with that cost shared equitably between the state and local
school systems according to local capacity to fund education through local tax revenues; and
WHEREAS, MFP Level 1 applies a series of weights, including low income and
English language learner (22%), career and technical education (6%), special education
(150%), gifted and talented (60%), and economy of scale (0-20%), to reflect varying student
needs; and
WHEREAS, MFP Level 2 provides incentives based on local effort and equalizes
differences among school systems with varying tax bases, reflecting longstanding policy
decisions regarding fairness in local contribution; and
WHEREAS, MFP Level 3 includes legislative allocations such as continuing pay
raises, historical formula provisions, and a per-student operational cost allocation for
expenses including health insurance, retirement, and fuel; and
WHEREAS, MFP Level 4 includes supplementary allocations and programs,
including compensation-related funding for teachers and support staff, along with additional
targeted initiatives added over time; and
