WHEREAS, compensation for certificated personnel and noncertificated support
workers has been renewed annually as early as the 2001-2002 school year within Levels 3
and 4 of the MFP; and
WHEREAS, the continued layering of formula components over decades, without
periodic redesign from first principles, has increased complexity, reduced transparency, and
limited the ability of the formula to clearly and consistently reflect present-day educational
priorities and fiscal constraints; and
WHEREAS, ensuring a durable and predictable compensation structure for teachers
and support staff, consistent with constitutional requirements and fiscal discipline, may
require a modernization and restructuring of the MFP to improve clarity, sustainability, and
long-term effectiveness; and
WHEREAS, the constitutional process requires the State Board of Elementary and
Secondary Education (BESE) to annually adopt the MFP formula, subject to approval by the
legislature, thereby establishing a structured but limited mechanism for modifying education
funding policy; and
WHEREAS, while the Constitution of Louisiana defines the framework and purpose
of the MFP, it does not prescribe specific formula components or methodologies, allowing
for periodic evaluation and potential restructuring to better meet the needs of students,
educators, and taxpayers; and
WHEREAS, the Louisiana Legislative Auditor has the authority to examine the
financial records of local school systems and evaluate compliance with the MFP, providing
an essential accountability function in ensuring effective use of public funds; and
WHEREAS, on March 11, 2026, the State Board of Elementary and Secondary
Education adopted a formula for the 2026-2027 fiscal year and submitted it to the legislature,
continuing the constitutionally required process for funding public education; and
WHEREAS, a comprehensive, top-to-bottom review of the MFP formula, its
structure, and its funding mechanisms is necessary to ensure that it remains equitable,
transparent, and sustainable and that it can support permanent and predictable compensation
for teachers and support staff in a manner consistent with the state's commitment to fiscal
discipline.
