THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Legislature of Louisiana does hereby
create and provide for a task force to conduct a comprehensive, top-to-bottom review of the
minimum foundation program formula and to develop a recommended restructured formula
framework that improves transparency, equity, predictability, and long-term sustainability,
including permanent and predictable funding mechanisms for pay raises for teachers and
support staff, and to submit a report with proposed recommendations and formula language
to the legislature and to the David R. Poynter Legislative Research Library as required by
R.S. 24:771 and 772, no later than January 1, 2027.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall not be limited to evaluating
incremental changes and is expressly authorized to develop recommendations from a zero
base, including a restructured or replacement formula model, without presuming the
continuation of the current Levels 1 through 4 or any existing legacy allocation.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall produce a proposed revised
or replacement formula structure, a proposed formula language suitable for consideration
within the constitutional MFP process, and a transition framework identifying how existing
allocations, weights, and legacy components should be consolidated, reweighted, phased,
or otherwise incorporated to achieve a modernized, coherent formula.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force's review shall include, at a
minimum:
(1) The historical development of the MFP, including major revisions and the
evolution of formula components and levels.
(2) Constitutional requirements for BESE's annual adoption of the formula and the
legislature's consideration of it, including the limits on legislative amendment of a formula
submitted by BESE.
(3) The appropriate placement, structure, and treatment of compensation funding for
teacher and support staff pay raises within any retained, revised, consolidated, replaced,
restructured, or newly recommended formula, including whether such funding should be
incorporated into the base, included through weights, provided as a separate recurring
allocation, or otherwise structured to improve equity, transparency, predictability, and
sustainability.
